00:01:25.040 --> 00:01:29.440
a little bit about data analysis workflows. And by workflows, I mean that the way that

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:35.680
you typically engage and interact with R as you're doing your analysis process. If you

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:40.599
are a user who is new to R or if you've ever worked with somebody who is just getting started

00:01:40.599 --> 00:01:45.320
with R, you typically see them using this sort of a workflow. They'll be typing R commands

00:01:45.320 --> 00:01:50.320
in the console and then looking at the result and the output of the commands and then issuing

00:01:50.320 --> 00:01:56.519
another command. So they sort of have this ad hoc conversation with R. Enter a command,

00:01:56.519 --> 00:02:02.839
look at the output, think a little bit, enter another command, look at the output, and so

00:02:02.839 --> 00:02:09.039
on. And there's actually nothing wrong with doing R this way. It's really fine for exploratory

00:02:09.039 --> 00:02:14.600
analysis in the early stages, but it has a very serious drawback which is that it is

00:02:14.600 --> 00:02:20.199
not reproducible. And this is one of the whole points of using a tool like R to do

00:02:20.199 --> 00:02:25.479
your data analysis is that you want your analysis to be very reproducible. But when you're just

00:02:25.479 --> 00:02:29.160
entering ad hoc statements, you're really not leaving much of a record besides your

00:02:29.160 --> 00:02:35.839
console history of what you did or why you did it or what the output was. And so most

00:02:35.839 --> 00:02:42.039
people who have used R for some time have learned that instead of just entering stuff

00:02:42.039 --> 00:02:47.520
ad hoc at the console most of the time, what you want to use is an R script. This is sort

00:02:47.520 --> 00:02:53.440
of another level above a regular like R console thing. It's instead of just entering stuff

00:02:53.440 --> 00:02:58.720
at the console, you're actually forming a script that leaves a record of what you have

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:07.279
done. And this has a huge amount of advantages over just entering code ad hoc at the console.

00:03:07.279 --> 00:03:11.479
Your analysis is now documented, like you have a record of what you did. It is also

00:03:11.479 --> 00:03:16.440
now repeatable, which is to say that you can now run the same analysis over and over as

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:21.240
you need to. And it's even shareable. You can take this .R file and send it to anybody

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:25.240
and say, hey, do you want to do the analysis that I just did? You know, there's no smoke

00:03:25.240 --> 00:03:34.479
and mirrors. Here's the thing that I did. So this is actually where many R users stop

00:03:34.479 --> 00:03:41.639
their exploration. So R scripts, output, done. But if you think about this workflow,

00:03:41.639 --> 00:03:46.839
it still actually has a lot of room for improvement. For one thing, the R output is disconnected

00:03:46.839 --> 00:03:53.119
from the input. Your R code, this script produces some output and it's really not connected

00:03:53.119 --> 00:04:00.119
in any way to the script itself. You have to save the output separately. Typically,

00:04:00.119 --> 00:04:06.080
this is not actually the end of the line. The data and the visualizations and the results

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:12.160
that are generated from your R code don't end their lives in the R console or in a viewer

00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:18.440
window in R studio. They actually end their lives somewhere else in a document or a presentation

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:25.079
or some other artifact that you're generating. And so when you need to re-perform your analysis,

00:04:25.079 --> 00:04:31.799
you have to do this export and copy and paste thing to try to get the results into their

00:04:31.799 --> 00:04:38.679
final format. And finally, the documentation in an R script is usually somewhat sparse.

00:04:38.679 --> 00:04:44.600
If you leave comments, that's great. Most people don't. And there's often not a lot

00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:50.119
of context for why you're doing what you're doing. So to solve a lot of these problems,

00:04:50.119 --> 00:04:54.799
we introduced something a few years back called R Markdown. It borrows heavily from

00:04:54.799 --> 00:05:00.760
some ideas in literate programming and it's designed to address some of the issues that

00:05:00.760 --> 00:05:07.519
I just talked about. R Markdown lets you do the same kind of thing you do in an R script,

00:05:07.519 --> 00:05:13.799
which is that you can write code and have a record of it, but it also allows you to

00:05:13.799 --> 00:05:20.320
bring together your output and your code in a rendered document so that your document

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:26.839
itself and the code are combined. This solves both of the problems I was talking about earlier.

00:05:26.839 --> 00:05:31.320
Now you can see your code and your output together. You can actually make your code

00:05:31.320 --> 00:05:36.720
your final document. They're one in the same artifact. And it is possible to create all

00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:40.959
kinds of very high quality professional documents from this. And you typically don't need to

00:05:40.959 --> 00:05:46.600
have another tool that you export this to. This can actually produce your final HTML

00:05:46.600 --> 00:05:54.480
file or PDF document or Word document or whatever that you need to email out. Even though this

00:05:54.480 --> 00:06:04.079
is a very powerful tool and it has received a lot of attention and a lot of accolades,

