release and it will come out soon. So here's an interesting one. So one person asked, does

00:41:02.199 --> 00:41:06.679
our Notebook work with Perl? The answer is yes, it does. Perl is one of the alternate

00:41:06.679 --> 00:41:15.000
engines. So you can have a Perl chunk just like you can have an R chunk. Somebody asked,

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:20.520
what languages are included in SQL? Funny you should ask. We are actually, we are working

00:41:20.520 --> 00:41:24.639
on this very thing. It is not ready yet, but before too long, you will be able to have

00:41:24.639 --> 00:41:35.280
a SQL chunk as well as an R chunk. Somebody asked, how does the Notebook interact with

00:41:35.280 --> 00:41:39.760
version control? For instance, the Jupyter Notebook does not play nice version control

00:41:39.760 --> 00:41:48.399
systems. Yes, so the way to think about this is that the Jupyter Notebook is a single file

00:41:48.399 --> 00:41:56.840
notebook. All of your code, all of your output, and configuration just lives in this one single

00:41:56.840 --> 00:42:03.919
notebook file. In RStudio, we have a two file system. So there is one file which is just

00:42:03.959 --> 00:42:10.239
the R Markdown file, it's plain text, and that contains all of your code. There's a

00:42:10.239 --> 00:42:14.760
second file which is the HTML file that I was showing you over here, and this thing

00:42:14.760 --> 00:42:19.000
has, this is a rendered copy which has an embedded, the rendered notebook which has

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:24.560
an embedded copy of your code. So if you want to use version control and you don't want

00:42:24.560 --> 00:42:30.080
noisy diffs, you can check in just your code to version control, and this is what we recommend

00:42:30.080 --> 00:42:36.479
for most cases, and what that means is that if somebody else opens up your notebook from

00:42:36.479 --> 00:42:39.919
the version control system, they won't see any of the code, the output from the code

00:42:39.919 --> 00:42:44.040
that you've run, they'll just see the code itself and they can run it for themselves.

00:42:44.040 --> 00:42:47.439
If you want to, you can also check in the second file so that everybody also sees all

00:42:47.439 --> 00:42:54.879
the same output, but then you're going to have some noisy diffs, and like I mentioned

00:42:54.879 --> 00:43:01.879
earlier, we are probably going to be improving the diffing system inside RStudio itself

00:43:01.879 --> 00:43:06.479
to make that a little bit easier, but for the most part, if you don't want noisy diffs,

00:43:06.479 --> 00:43:10.120
you just want to check in the code, not the output HTML file.

00:43:10.120 --> 00:43:15.360
Oh, here's a very good question. When you render a notebook, is the analysis performed

00:43:15.360 --> 00:43:21.000
in a separate environment as it currently is with NIDAR? And the answer is, no, it is

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:24.719
not, and that's a really good question because it's important to understand for the execution

00:43:24.719 --> 00:43:30.040
model. When you run code in the notebook, it's actually executed in your current R session.

00:43:30.040 --> 00:43:34.399
It is not executed in some sort of separate session that can't see any variables. I'll

00:43:34.399 --> 00:43:39.800
give you a quick demo to show you how this works and help you understand it.

00:43:39.800 --> 00:43:48.719
So, here's my notebook again. So, let's say, let's go open up the console. So, I'm going

00:43:48.719 --> 00:44:01.879
to go open up the console in my notebook, and I'm going to create something called

00:44:01.879 --> 00:44:09.639
a variable called x. I'll give that the value, I don't know, 25 and 53. Those are good numbers.

00:44:09.639 --> 00:44:15.760
So now, if I add a new chunk in here, and I just print out the value of x, you can see

00:44:15.760 --> 00:44:21.120
there it is. So, this is actually happening in the same R session as your console. You

00:44:21.120 --> 00:44:27.879
can think of running notebook code as running it right at the console. It's very similar.

00:44:27.879 --> 00:44:34.520
So, somebody asked, is notebook compatible with any type of interactive graph? The answer

00:44:34.520 --> 00:44:40.520
is yes, it is. In fact, here is an interactive graph. It is very easy to use interactive

00:44:40.520 --> 00:44:46.120
graphs. Any HTML widget is supported, not just this particular one.

00:44:46.120 --> 00:44:56.399
So, somebody asked, can I use this on shinyapps.io? This is a good question because the answer

00:44:56.399 --> 00:45:04.679
is that you currently can't. So, shinyapps.io is only for, it's only for shiny applications,

00:45:04.679 --> 00:45:09.159
and notebooks are not shiny applications. There are markdown files, and they're not

00:45:09.159 --> 00:45:20.439
even shiny markdown files, they're just regular, no server required, static HTML files. So,

00:45:20.439 --> 00:45:28.239
those can be published to RPUBs, or they can also be published to really anything that

00:45:28.239 --> 00:45:37.439
supports static HTML. Somebody asked, what happens to interactive graphics when you share

00:45:37.439 --> 00:45:47.280
the notebook output? That's a good question. So, if you have used shiny documents or shiny,

00:45:47.280 --> 00:45:51.719
you know that if you have interactivity, then you're typically going to need a server to

00:45:51.719 --> 00:45:58.719
run to drive the interactivity. And so, you might rightly ask, if I have a notebook that

00:45:58.719 --> 00:46:02.800
has one of these interactive widgets in it, what's going to happen if I go to share that

00:46:02.800 --> 00:46:06.919
with somebody? And the answer is that it's going to work just fine, and the reason is

00:46:06.919 --> 00:46:12.320
that the only thing, the only kind of interactivity that is currently supported inside notebooks

00:46:12.320 --> 00:46:18.080
is HTML widgets, and those don't need a server. They run entirely off code and data that is

00:46:18.080 --> 00:46:24.080
embedded inside the HTML. So, unless you're publishing to a format that inherently does

00:46:24.080 --> 00:46:28.959
not support interactivity, such as a PDF or Word document, the interactivity is actually

00:46:28.959 --> 00:46:35.800
going to work just fine. In fact, I'm going to, I'll demonstrate that for you. So, here's

00:46:35.800 --> 00:46:39.360
our demonstration notebook that we just made, and you'll see that this HTML widget, which

00:46:39.360 --> 00:46:44.040
includes interactivity, just continues to work fine right inside the web browser. There's

00:46:44.040 --> 00:46:53.199
no R required. You can publish this to any static web host. Somebody asked, can you enter

00:46:53.199 --> 00:47:03.959
tech-like equations, etc., into the notebook? That is a good question. The answer is, it's

00:47:03.959 --> 00:47:08.879
not incredibly easy to do right now, but that is something that we are currently working

00:47:08.879 --> 00:47:15.360
on. So, somebody asked, can we use our Shiny server to host notebooks? And the answer to

00:47:15.360 --> 00:47:21.919
that is, not really, and there's really no need to do it because notebooks are not Shiny,

00:47:21.919 --> 00:47:26.879
so you don't need Shiny server. You can use whatever web browser, whatever web, whatever

00:47:26.879 --> 00:47:33.560
host you want. Alright, somebody said, how can I save a plot from the notebook? I right

00:47:33.560 --> 00:47:39.280
click the mouse on the figure to save, but I don't know where it goes. Thanks. So, if

00:47:39.280 --> 00:47:46.600
you want to save just one plot from the notebook, I would say don't, there's really no need

00:47:46.600 --> 00:47:52.040
to use notebooks at all. You can right click and download the thing if you really want

00:47:52.040 --> 00:47:58.760
to, but like you mentioned, it doesn't go anywhere useful. So, what I would do there

00:47:58.760 --> 00:48:10.560
is actually just take the code, run it at the console, and then you can export that

00:48:10.560 --> 00:48:16.600
as an image, however you like. So, the notebook is not designed to support this sort of workflow

00:48:16.600 --> 00:48:22.699
where you're putting stuff elsewhere on the file system. If you want to take just one

00:48:22.699 --> 00:48:30.300
piece and export it, I would recommend just running that one piece at the console, and

00:48:30.300 --> 00:48:33.459
fortunately because the notebook works inside your main environment, you can actually get

00:48:33.459 --> 00:48:39.419
all of your data set up to run that line of code using your notebook, and then you can

00:48:39.419 --> 00:48:49.219
run just that line outside the notebook to generate the plot. So, somebody asked, how

00:48:49.219 --> 00:48:54.699
easy is it to insert external graphics into the notebook? The answer to that question

00:48:54.699 --> 00:49:03.340
is it is possible to insert them into the rendered notebook. For instance, it's just

